  title={How does the public charging network fuel plug-in electric vehicle uptake?},
  author={Burra, Lavan T and Cirillo, Cinzia and Linn, Joshua},
  year={2024},
  publisher={Working paper},
  abstract={Limited empirical evidence exists regarding the distributional impacts of public charging network in driving the plug-in electric vehicle (PEV) uptake. Alongside, governments are expanding subsidies for public charging stations to achieve equitable access and a wider fast charging network. Given these policy priorities, we investigate the heterogeneous effects of public charging infrastructure on PEV adoption using a novel research design and data covering the entire US from 2010 to 2020. Our results show a stronger and more persistent
demand response for PEVs with access to level 3 public chargers, remaining significant even when located at greater distances from the residential zip code. Moreover, public chargers primarily influence higher-income and urban/suburban residents. Notably, low-income and rural residents show no significant increase in PEV demand with public charging access, highlighting potential disparities in PEV adoption}
